posts.com: >"Women with complete androgen insensitivity syndrome (CAIS) have "excellent" breast development that's described as "normal", "full", "complete", and "well-developed", as well as "generous" and "typically above-average" in size (Morris, 1953; Adams et al., 1970; Weisberg, Malkasian, & Pratt, 1970; Dewhurst, 1971; Glenn, 1976; Patterson, McPhaul, & Hughes, 1994; Quigley et al., 1995; McPhaul, 2002; Galani et al., 2008; Oakes et al., 2008; Tiefenbacher & Daxenbichler, 2008; Barbieri, 2017). They have even been reported as having "voluptuous breasts" (Roy Hertz et al., 1966; Valentine, 1969; Polani, 1970). John McLean Morris, the gynecologist who reviewed and summarized all of the existing scientific literature on CAIS women in 1953 (including 82 cases) and gave their condition the (now-obsolete) name "testicular feminization", described their breasts as "unusually large" and "jumbo-sized" (Morris, 1953; Quigley et al., 1995). He additionally said in his famous 1953 review that they had "normal female breasts, often with a tendency to be overdeveloped" (Morris, 1953). In actuality however, some CAIS women have large breasts while some have small breasts (Wisniewski et al., 2000), and we have no clear data that their breasts are in fact larger on average. The variation in breast growth in CAIS women parallels the same large variation in breast size between individuals that's seen in women in general.

Maybe, but it's a gamble. Some people regain all their hair, some regain none. If it's been ten years, though, I think you may be out of luck. I don't think it's common to regain more than a year or two worth of hair loss. HRT may not stop your hair loss at all, just look at the boomer trannies and IT'S MA'AMs who started late in life and probably had pretty high test before, the damage is already done. FtMs who detransition naturally produce E and they don't regain their lost hair either. Definitely a case of you want to start as early as possible.

If hair is all you care about though, you don't need E, and it probably shouldn't be anywhere near the top of the list of options. E inhibits hair loss as a side effect, the actual thing that stops hair loss is low testosterone. Higher E levels will dampen your T, that's how monotherapy works, but E will have other effects, including breasts, which is going to be a problem if you want to present as conventionally masculine. No, it's not as simple as "I'll just bind if they get too big", you'll also get a different weight distribution and skin oils, people will notice, and binding isn't comfortably even with a smaller chest.

I suggest you do what the rich people do, get a hair transplant and take an antiandrogen. You can do the transplant in Thailand or Turkey or somewhere to save money on that (but it's still quite expensive, save up), and buy Chinese fina or Brazilian antiandrogen pills to selfmedicate. That doesn't mean that you're not trans, although you might not be trans. I'm not trying to tell you that you are or pinkpill you or anything like that. But, like, 100% certainty is a lot to have on something more fuzzy like this. I think there will always be a speck of doubt somewhere, especially because of what society says about us, it gets to you. But like you can ask yourself some questions in your head, stuff like, "would I press a button that made it so I was me but if I was born as a cis girl and everyone acted like I always was a girl?" or "would I transition if I knew I'd pass and it was totally socially acceptable?" or even like "if I took a couple tests and they said that I'm most likely (male/female/trans/cis (think separately for each one)), how would it make me feel?" or "would I rather be an average and decent looking cis woman or the hottest man on earth?" stuff like that. I think basically everyone who transitions, unless they're completely unhinged, worries about the social consequences and all of the pain and effort that goes into transition and about if they'll pass or not. It's just like, once the pain of how they're living surpasses their fear of what could happen, they don't care as much anymore and they transition.

It's heavy and it's a lot of processing to do but I don't think I'd just say you're definitely not based on that. Like, if you pressed the hypothetical "turn into a cis girl" button from that question...

Goal of the thread: Go out for a walk, or try to get any other form of small exercise (walking stairs for 5 mins for example)
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

But one thing that you need to keep in mind about looks is that perspective and aesthetics are not entirely rational things, and that it is sometimes for the best to recall that you can mold your views as time passes more by habituation than by trying to argue your way out of feeling like that.

>>28882846
your pain is not validated by how deeply you can cut yourself but by your ability to recognize and acknowledge it. the sharp sting of the cut, the physical mark, the bleeding - these all cause you and others to further recognize your pain, but they aren't the only thing that can do this. your pain, your suffering, your agony, even your apathy - these are all already valid emotions without the marks on your arm.

i thought i'd inevitably train myself to cut deeper until i could kill myself doing it - instead, i just wound up with a bunch of vertical scars that make people's eye widen when they notice them on my pale skin. i don't regret anything i've ever done, but i firmly consider cutting myself a mistake. one with valuable lessons, but a mistake.

when i call this shit 'pussy shit,' it's not because it's not deeper - though that does require a certain kind of bravery or stupidity - it's because you're likely realizing it's not productive or helpful and on the verge of getting addicted to feeling that pain, watching the blood flow, making some sort of alteration that you won't be able to step back as proof of what you're going through.

for what it's worth, i believe that you're hurting. i believe that your pain is real. but what would get me to believe it's more real than anything is you admitting to yourself it's real without this. bravery isn't cutting deeper, it's sitting beside your pain and restraining that urge to prove it to yourself on your body. it's looking deep in its eye and letting it know you can see it and that you're going to do something about it.

that promise ring is something beautiful you did for yourself - a commitment you made to see something through and a proof of your resolve. it's brave to follow those hopes and dreams because they'll cause more pain than you could ever put on your arm and bring much more beauty.

i know this may sound like shallow advice because i cannot possibly ever be that person for you or know you well enough to fight your specific faults - but i formerly considered myself unsalvageable, a caustic poison, an incurable disease. that i deserved being left every time it happened. every time someone left me i felt it was the last time and the next one would do me in. i attempted suicide times in-between a few times.

but you have to keep trying. you have to keep believing. it is an incredible pain to stay that open and watch where it can go knowing it might end in another loss, but that effort is always worth it if only to prove to yourself you have the courage to keep trying to no matter what. love requires sincerity and being open even in the face of loss and rejection means that you while you will experience more pain, you will also be able to attract someone who will really love you for who you are.

if you're annoying or clingy, those don't even have to be bad things - some people love that shit. i was annoying and clingy and i'm now the leader of my social group and maintain hang-outs and close friendships with numerous people i've known for years and years. i live with someone who was unemployable and barely surviving with me on my SSI six years ago and now has a management job in IT. long but beautiful journey.

keep trying. love is always worth it. sincerity, effort, openness - these create their own beauty because they reveal what is already beautiful: you. someone will appreciate it.

it's important to consider that whether you attach "rape" or "sexual assault" to the words you begin to associate these memories with that you first and foremost acknowledge that this has hurt you badly and that you don't have to 'earn' validity, you already have it. this has very obviously done something to you and deserves to be taken seriously. you don't need us to prove to yourself that your pain is real, but if it helps, i believe you very firmly.

therapy can help get you through these things, but it can be hard to find the right therapist that will really help you, and they can come pre-loaded with discourse on how you should react to this that may push you in one direction or another. it's worth looking for a good one, but more importantly and firstly -

i really suggest finding friends who will listen to you thoroughly whenever you're feeling down. people who don't tell you what to do or how to react, but just help you sort through how you feel you want to take this. people who will listen to you, affirm your feelings, and just be there for a hug or whatever you need. tons of anons on here have been through some horrible shit, i guarantee with your openness you can find empathetic, trusting people to hear you out on here.

you can absolutely get through this.

The recipe I use for eggnog goes like this:

12 egg yolks
1 cup of sugar
2 cups heavy cream
4 cups whole milk
About a teaspoon nutmeg
A pinch of salt
teaspoon vanilla
teaspoon of cinnamon

You have to heat the sugar, cream, and milk up then use that mixture to temper the eggs.
Then put it back on the heat until it will evenly coat your spoon (or until it reaches a medium-thickness)
Then add the spices and take it off heat, refrigerate and serve.
I like to add a bit of aged rum or some whiskey as well, but that's up to the drinker's discretion

I also have a recipe for shortbread jam cookies but I need to make sure I have the right proportions.
